# Major Subsystems

Instead of thinking "CPU," think of the accelerator as several cooperating hardware engines.

## 1. Command Processor

The Command Processor is the "front door" of the accelerator.

It accepts requests from software.

Example command:

```
Multiply Matrix A and Matrix B

Store result in Tensor C

Apply ReLU

Signal completion
```

Responsibilities:

* Decode commands
* Configure hardware
* Validate parameters
* Launch execution
* Generate interrupts

---

## 2. Instruction Scheduler

The scheduler is the "brain."

It decides:

```
DMA first?

Compute first?

Wait?

Overlap?

Prioritize?
```

The scheduler keeps every hardware unit busy.

A good scheduler can improve throughput dramatically without changing the compute hardware.

---

## 3. DMA Engine

Moving data is often more expensive than computing on it.

The DMA engine fetches tensors from DDR into local SRAM without involving a CPU.

```text
DDR

↓

DMA

↓

Local SRAM

↓

Compute
```

It also writes results back asynchronously.

Future versions could support:

* double buffering
* scatter-gather
* prefetching

---

## 4. Local SRAM (Scratchpad)

Unlike CPUs, AI accelerators often use managed scratchpad memories instead of caches.

Why?

Because tensor access patterns are predictable.

Advantages:

* deterministic latency
* higher bandwidth
* lower power
* easier verification

---

## 5. Matrix Compute Engine

This is the heart of the accelerator.

Initially it supports:

```
C = A × B + C
```

This is GEMM (General Matrix Multiply), which underpins much of deep learning.

Internally, it contains:

```text
Input Buffers

↓

MAC Array

↓

Accumulator

↓

Output Buffer
```

---

## 6. MAC Array

The MAC (Multiply-Accumulate) array performs:

```
A × B + Accumulator
```

Many MACs operate in parallel.

Example:

```
16 × 16

256 MACs
```

Later, you can scale to:

* 32×32
* 64×64

The interface stays the same.

---

## 7. Accumulator

Intermediate sums are stored here.

Example:

```
A × B

↓

Partial Sum

↓

Partial Sum

↓

Partial Sum

↓

Final Output
```

This allows large matrix operations to be broken into tiles.

---

## 8. Output Buffer

Results are staged before DMA writes them back to memory.

This decouples computation from memory transfers.

---

## 9. Performance Monitor Unit (PMU)

This is one of the features that makes the project feel "production-quality."

The PMU collects metrics such as:

* cycles executed
* MAC utilization
* memory bandwidth
* DMA wait time
* scheduler stalls
* idle cycles
* command latency

These metrics will later feed your AI Performance Agent.

---

## 10. Debug Infrastructure

Every professional ASIC includes observability.

We'll include:

* command trace
* hardware event logs
* performance counters
* error registers
* assertion status
* optional trace buffers

This makes debugging practical.

